data.name: Watch What Matthew Perry Says When A Dude Says His Drug Addiction Is His Choice
data.caption: www.upworthy.com
data.description: Could he BE any more awesome?

data.message: I actually thought he didn't do very well on this..neither of them did. They both just kept throwing childish retorts at each other, only the woman was actually trying to contribute anything worthwhile to the debate.
Addiction was not his choice but choosing to do drugs was! Also developing healthy coping mechanisms helps one avoid the pitfalls of drugs and drug addiction.
If you've never had an addiction you dont have business commenting on someone who has or does. If addiction is a choice so is being ugly and fat.
Choosing to try drugs is a choice. Becoming addicted is not.
I might get some hassle for this, and drug addiction is a serious issue, but I have to say it is a choice. In most cases nobody forces someone to take drugs.

this is stupid. "allergy of the body". What the fuck does that even mean? This only proves that people are inclined to believe the celebrity's perspective. He made weak ad hominem arguments, and he egotistically acted like he was moderating the discussion. Why the hell was he there, anyways? Fuck Matthew Perry, and his alcoholism. It's not a disease, it's a fucking choice. I overindulge in alcohol because I choose to, and I know it's wrong, but I do it anyways because it's a convenient way to make me feel better right now. I'm weak, and I know it. I don't have a disease, I have a problem with will power. So does Matthew Perry.
Initially it is a choice, unless you're born addicted. After repeated use, it restructures your brain...the need or desire to use becomes less of a conscious decision.

Unless you've been one of the fortunate few who've never so much as sipped a beer or taken a hit off of a marijuana cigarette or needed a narcotic pain reliever, you chose to put something into your body without having any idea whether or not you'd be one of those who would not be able to stop.

Why do you suppose some people can drink "normally", socially, and others can't?  Do you honestly believe that anyone CHOOSES to pay the consequences associated with addiction?  Loss of jobs, homes, families, friends, dignity, self respect?

I'll tell you how much it's NOT about "will power".  I used drugs AGAINST my own will!  I used when I didnt' want to.  I used when I'd promised myself I wouldn't.  Why?  Because I'm so weak willed?  Hardly.  The reason is because I'm an addict.  I'm grateful to have been in recovery for nearly 11 years now but it took years of suffering, of not understanding why I couldn't stop even though I wanted to, of shame and guilt and losses.

I'd love to be able to have a glass of wine with dinner, coctails with friends after work, even take a toke on a joint now and then but I can't.  My brain and my body don't work like the brains and bodies of those who can.

Criminalizing the manufacture and dealing of drugs... I'm good with that.  Those people are predators.  Criminilizing addiction is absurd, ludicrous, ineffective, inhumane and a waste of taxpayer dollars.  Addicts require treatment in order to get better.

Yes, I chose to try that first joint, drink that first drink, but like many of you, I had no idea that it would lead to a life time of misery and loss of control over my own thoughts and body.  Lots of my friends tried those first experiences with me.  Lots of them went on to stop partying and begin adult lives.  Lots of us didn't.  The latter of us have a disorder, called addiction.
"My life is the objective evidence." That is actually the definition of subjective evidence...
Sure, people choose to drink or take a drug, but no one chooses to be an addict. Stop moralizing and realize that addiction is complicated disease.
<= sick of the current culture of excuses. It IS a choice.

Having addiction labelled as a disease, once again, removes responsibility of an individual from his/her actions. It's another liberal policy of "I'm not responsible for what I do" and "it's the responsibility of others to help me/support me, etc." It is a choice to do drugs, and if you take a couple of drinks and find that you can't stop, it's that person's responsibility to seek help for themselves! Good grief!

My dad was an alcoholic. I attended my first AA meeting before I was a week old, as he decided to get sober 11 months before I was born. My dad never said, "I'm Greg and I'm an alcoholic." He said, I'm an alcoholic and my problem is Greg." The disease is not a choice, but it is also not to blame for your choices.
'The Dude' is Peter Hitchens. A well known rightwing nutcase/mouthpiece. You get O'Reilly - We get Hitchens apparently.
I don't think Perry did a good job of defending himself at all.

it's not really on point, he misses most opportunities given to him to give real information or insight by dishing out quips. He's brought sassiness to an intellectual debate without much in the way of figures to back it up. I'd like to have listened more to the person by his side who was actually armed with information.
It was his choice initially, after that it was out of his control

I love Matthew Perry now more than ever. That obnoxious British assmunch needs to be tarred and feathered though. Addiction is NOT a choice. It is a disease. And coupled with mental illness, as it so often is, makes it a killer. Don't start with me, you will not win. (I work in this field.)
Unfortunately he looks as if he's been sitting at a bar stool for 3 days.
I don't think this debate really achieved anything...
At some point, the addict CHOOSES to engage in the drug.  CHOOSES.  FACT.

As a Briton, I would like to take this opportunity to apologise for Peter Hitchens. He's an odious little man, who, along with Piers Morgan, needs to be sealed up inside a barrel and dropped into the north sea.

The only people who should get a say in this are either researchers or former addicts. No one else truly gets it. Not everyone who has that first drink or first line becomes an addict - in fact the vast majority don't. Those are the people who have a choice to stop or start or whatever. It is those few who have a genetic disposition to addiction that innocently have that first drink or that first sample of some drug that then can't stop - they no longer have a choice. They didn't make the decision to become addicts, they just did what nearly everyone else does, have a casual drink or try some drug that everyone else is enjoying and then they discover the disease. Up until then, they think they are normal and can just stop whenever they want. Until you have experience this kind of addiction, this uncontrollable obsession, you don't have a dog in this fight.

Really, people? Do any of you even have an iota of empathy in your brains for people who end up addicted to substances because those substances are the only escape from your pain?? You can demonize drugs and alcohol all you want, but, remember, nearly ALL "illegal" drugs were once widely used as MEDICINE. And, yes, they still DO have very effective medicinal qualities, in many cases better than what you get at the pharmacy. The idea that addiction is a choice is ludicrous, and shaming anyone (non-addicted) who wants to get high once in a while is the ultimate hypocracy. That buzz from a beer or a cigarette? The adrenaline from playing football, boxing, running, or even just watching a game? That's a HIGH. You "need" coffee to function? Well, that's also substance abuse. Why is it we can point at so many laws and complain about their rudiculousness UNLESS it's in regards to drugs and their usage and punishments?
Perry gets owned in this. Hitchens is a pompous arse but rhetorically he beats him all ends up. The prof is the most accurate because she's taken the trouble to do her homework. Bing bing:)
